#What is the difference between copy() and deep copy for lists?

copy() (or list[:]) makes a SHALLOW copy — nested objects still share the same reference. 
deepcopy() from the copy module creates fully independent nested objects.

import copy
original = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]

shallow = original.copy() # or original[:]
deep = copy.deepcopy(original)

original[0][0] = 99 # modify nested list

print(original) # [[99, 2], [3, 4]]
print(shallow) # [[99, 2], [3, 4]] <- CHANGED (same ref)
print(deep) # [[1, 2], [3, 4]] <- unchanged
